I need a detailed implementation plan for adding a custom theme system to the T3 Code editor (a React/Tailwind/Vite monorepo). Here is everything you need to know.

## Constraints
- Do NOT modify build config or add new dependencies
- `bun lint` and `bun typecheck` must pass

## What needs to be built
1. A `ThemeId` union type + `ThemeDefinition` interface + 3 built-in theme objects in `packages/shared/src/theme.ts`. Themes: "t3-dark", "t3-light", "t3-midnight". Colors needed: background, foreground, accent, sidebar, editor, terminal, statusBar.
2. A `ThemeProvider` context + `useTheme` hook in `apps/web/src/components/ThemeProvider.tsx`. Persists `ThemeId` to localStorage key `t3code:app-theme`. Applies `data-theme="<id>"` attribute and `.dark` class to `document.documentElement`. Uses `useSyncExternalStore` + React Context pattern.
3. A `ThemeSelector` component in `apps/web/src/components/ThemeSelector.tsx` with visual preview swatches for each theme.
4. CSS for 3 complete theme palettes using `[data-theme="..."]` attribute selectors that override all CSS custom properties.
5. Wire everything into the existing settings page and root route.

## Existing codebase context

### `packages/shared/package.json` (subpath exports)
```json
{
  "name": "@t3tools/shared",
  "exports": {
    "./model": { "types": "./src/model.ts", "import": "./src/model.ts" },
    "./git": { "types": "./src/git.ts", "import": "./src/git.ts" },
    "./logging": { "types": "./src/logging.ts", "import": "./src/logging.ts" },
    "./shell": { "types": "./src/shell.ts", "import": "./src/shell.ts" },
    "./Net": { "types": "./src/Net.ts", "import": "./src/Net.ts" }
  },
  "dependencies": { "@t3tools/contracts": "workspace:*", "effect": "catalog:" }
}
```

### Existing `apps/web/src/hooks/useTheme.ts` (must remain importable from same path; re-export from ThemeProvider is fine)
```typescript
type Theme = "light" | "dark" | "system";
// Module-level store with useSyncExternalStore
// Storage key: "t3code:theme"
// Applies .dark class to document.documentElement
// exports: useTheme() returning { theme, setTheme, resolvedTheme }
```
Note: The settings page currently imports `useTheme` from `"../hooks/useTheme"` and uses `{ theme, setTheme, resolvedTheme }`. We're REPLACING this API with the new one, so the settings page will be updated too.

### `apps/web/src/index.css` - Tailwind v4 CSS with:
```css
@import "tailwindcss";
@custom-variant dark (&:is(.dark, .dark *));
@theme inline {
  --color-background: var(--background);
  --color-foreground: var(--foreground);
  /* ... many more --color-X mappings ... */
  --radius-sm: calc(var(--radius) - 4px);
  /* ... */
}
:root {
  color-scheme: light;
  --background: var(--color-white);
  --foreground: var(--color-neutral-800);
  /* ... all light mode vars ... */
  @variant dark {
    color-scheme: dark;
    --background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--color-neutral-950) 95%, var(--color-white));
    /* ... all dark mode vars ... */
  }
}
```
Key detail: `:root:is(.dark, .dark *)` from the custom dark variant has specificity 0-2-0. So theme selectors need to use `:root[data-theme="..."]` (specificity 0-2-0 too) placed AFTER `:root` to win the cascade.

### `apps/web/src/routes/__root.tsx`
```tsx
function RootRouteView() {
  if (!readNativeApi()) return <div>Connecting...</div>;
  return (
    <ToastProvider>
      <AnchoredToastProvider>
        <EventRouter />
        <DesktopProjectBootstrap />
        <Outlet />
      </AnchoredToastProvider>
    </ToastProvider>
  );
}
```
ThemeProvider should wrap this JSX tree. The best place is wrapping the JSX return from `RootRouteView`.

### `apps/web/src/routes/_chat.settings.tsx` - Appearance section
```tsx
const THEME_OPTIONS = [
  { value: "system", label: "System", ... },
  { value: "light", label: "Light", ... },
  { value: "dark", label: "Dark", ... },
] as const;

// In component:
const { theme, setTheme, resolvedTheme } = useTheme();
// Renders radio buttons using THEME_OPTIONS
// Shows "Active theme: {resolvedTheme}"
```
This needs to be replaced with the new ThemeSelector component and new useTheme API.

### `apps/web/src/router.ts`
```tsx
Wrap: ({ children }) => createElement(QueryClientProvider, ..., createElement(StoreProvider, null, children))
```
ThemeProvider should NOT go here (it renders JSX); `__root.tsx` is the right place.

## Design decisions for the plan

### ThemeProvider implementation approach
Use React Context + `useSyncExternalStore` for optimal rendering:
- Module-level store (like existing useTheme.ts) for the subscription
- React Context for passing themeId + themeDefinition + setTheme to components
- On module load: immediately apply stored theme (prevent flash)
- `applyTheme(id, suppressTransitions?)`:
  - `document.documentElement.dataset.theme = id`
  - toggle `.dark` class based on `theme.colorScheme === "dark"`
  - suppress transitions with `no-transitions` class (reuse existing pattern)

### CSS cascade strategy
Use `:root[data-theme="t3-dark"]` selectors (specificity 0-2-0 = same as dark variant), placed AFTER `:root { @variant dark {...} }` block so they win the cascade. Each selector sets ALL CSS variables to be self-contained.

### ThemeSelector swatches
Each swatch shows:
- Theme name
- A mini color grid using the theme's colors (background, sidebar, accent, terminal)
- Selected state with primary-colored ring
- Accessible button with role="radio"

### The new useTheme API
```typescript
interface ThemeContextValue {
  themeId: ThemeId;
  themeDefinition: ThemeDefinition;
  setTheme: (id: ThemeId) => void;
}
```
`apps/web/src/hooks/useTheme.ts` becomes a thin re-export:
```typescript
export { useTheme, ThemeProvider } from "../components/ThemeProvider";
```

### Settings page update
Replace the old Appearance section:
- Remove `THEME_OPTIONS`, `theme`, `setTheme`, `resolvedTheme` from old API
- Import and render `<ThemeSelector />` inside the Appearance section
- Show `themeDefinition.name` as the active theme name

## Please produce a step-by-step implementation plan

For each file, describe:
1. What to create/change
2. The exact structure/content with enough detail to implement without guessing
3. The color values for each theme (design thoughtful, consistent palettes)

Make sure the plan is self-contained and executable without further research.

