I now have everything I need. Here is the complete, self-contained implementation plan.

---

## Implementation Plan: Custom Theme System for T3 Code

### Overview

Six files need to be created or modified:

1. `packages/shared/src/theme.ts` - new file: types + theme data
2. `packages/shared/package.json` - add `./theme` subpath export
3. `apps/web/src/components/ThemeProvider.tsx` - new file: store + context + hook
4. `apps/web/src/hooks/useTheme.ts` - replace entirely with a thin re-export
5. `apps/web/src/components/ThemeSelector.tsx` - new file: swatch UI
6. `apps/web/src/index.css` - add three `[data-theme]` palette blocks
7. `apps/web/src/routes/__root.tsx` - wrap tree in `ThemeProvider`
8. `apps/web/src/routes/_chat.settings.tsx` - replace Appearance section

---

### Step 1: `packages/shared/src/theme.ts` (new file)

This is a pure data/type module. It must not import from `effect` or `@t3tools/contracts` since it needs no Effect machinery. The module has no side effects and works in both browser and server environments.

Structure:

```typescript
export type ThemeId = "t3-dark" | "t3-light" | "t3-midnight";

export interface ThemeDefinition {
  readonly id: ThemeId;
  readonly name: string;
  readonly colorScheme: "dark" | "light";
  readonly colors: {
    readonly background: string;
    readonly foreground: string;
    readonly accent: string;
    readonly sidebar: string;
    readonly editor: string;
    readonly terminal: string;
    readonly statusBar: string;
  };
}

export const THEMES: Record<ThemeId, ThemeDefinition> = { ... };

export const THEME_IDS: readonly ThemeId[] = ["t3-dark", "t3-light", "t3-midnight"];

export const DEFAULT_THEME_ID: ThemeId = "t3-dark";

export function isThemeId(value: unknown): value is ThemeId { ... }

export function getTheme(id: ThemeId): ThemeDefinition { ... }
```

The colors object serves double duty: it feeds the `ThemeSelector` swatches directly (no need to parse CSS) and also documents what each CSS variable maps to conceptually. These values are primarily for the swatch rendering, not injected as inline styles into the document — the actual theming is done by CSS custom property overrides.

**Theme palette design:**

`"t3-dark"` (the default dark theme, warm neutral):
- `colorScheme: "dark"`
- `background: "#0f0f11"` - near-black with slight warm tone
- `foreground: "#e8e8ec"` - soft white
- `accent: "#7c6af7"` - violet-purple (primary brand)
- `sidebar: "#141418"` - slightly lighter than background
- `editor: "#0c0c0e"` - deepest surface for code
- `terminal: "#0a0a0c"` - darkest, distinct from editor
- `statusBar: "#1a1a22"` - separated strip with violet tint

`"t3-light"` (clean professional light theme):
- `colorScheme: "light"`
- `background: "#ffffff"` - pure white
- `foreground: "#1a1a2e"` - deep navy-neutral text
- `accent: "#5a4fcf"` - muted violet (contrast-safe on white)
- `sidebar: "#f4f4f8"` - very faint grey
- `editor: "#fafafa"` - near white, barely distinct
- `terminal: "#f0f0f4"` - slightly more grey for terminal surface
- `statusBar: "#ebebf2"` - subtle separation

`"t3-midnight"` (deep blue-black, high contrast cool theme):
- `colorScheme: "dark"`
- `background: "#080c14"` - very dark blue-black
- `foreground: "#cdd9f0"` - cool blue-white
- `accent: "#4d9ef7"` - bright cornflower blue
- `sidebar: "#0c1120"` - dark blue with slight navy cast
- `editor: "#060a12"` - deeper than background
- `terminal: "#050810"` - deepest dark with blue undertone
- `statusBar: "#0e1829"` - blue-tinted status strip

The `THEMES` record and `THEME_IDS` array provide all the data the UI components need. `isThemeId` is a type guard used in the store when parsing localStorage. `getTheme` is a convenience accessor that returns the definition (never undefined since the union is exhaustive).

---

### Step 2: `packages/shared/package.json` — add `./theme` subpath export

Add one entry to the `"exports"` map:

```json
"./theme": {
  "types": "./src/theme.ts",
  "import": "./src/theme.ts"
}
```

This follows the exact same pattern as `./model`, `./git`, etc. No build configuration changes; this package uses source files directly (as confirmed by the existing export entries all pointing to `./src/*.ts`).

---

### Step 3: `apps/web/src/components/ThemeProvider.tsx` (new file)

This file contains three things: the module-level store, the React context, and the exported hook. It replaces the logic in `hooks/useTheme.ts`.

**Module-level store (mirrors `appSettings.ts` and `hooks/useTheme.ts` patterns):**

```typescript
import { createContext, useCallback, useContext, useSyncExternalStore, type ReactNode } from "react";
import {
  DEFAULT_THEME_ID,
  THEME_IDS,
  getTheme,
  isThemeId,
  type ThemeDefinition,
  type ThemeId,
} from "@t3tools/shared/theme";

const STORAGE_KEY = "t3code:app-theme";

let listeners: Array<() => void> = [];
let lastThemeId: ThemeId | null = null;

function emitChange(): void {
  for (const listener of listeners) listener();
}

function getStoredThemeId(): ThemeId {
  const raw = localStorage.getItem(STORAGE_KEY);
  return isThemeId(raw) ? raw : DEFAULT_THEME_ID;
}

function applyTheme(id: ThemeId, suppressTransitions = false): void {
  const theme = getTheme(id);
  if (suppressTransitions) {
    document.documentElement.classList.add("no-transitions");
  }
  document.documentElement.dataset["theme"] = id;
  document.documentElement.classList.toggle("dark", theme.colorScheme === "dark");
  if (suppressTransitions) {
    // oxlint-disable-next-line no-unused-expressions
    document.documentElement.offsetHeight;
    requestAnimationFrame(() => {
      document.documentElement.classList.remove("no-transitions");
    });
  }
}

// Apply immediately on module load to prevent flash
applyTheme(getStoredThemeId());

function getSnapshot(): ThemeId {
  const id = getStoredThemeId();
  if (lastThemeId === id) return lastThemeId;
  lastThemeId = id;
  return id;
}

function subscribe(listener: () => void): () => void {
  listeners.push(listener);
  const handleStorage = (e: StorageEvent) => {
    if (e.key === STORAGE_KEY) {
      applyTheme(getStoredThemeId(), true);
      emitChange();
    }
  };
  window.addEventListener("storage", handleStorage);
  return () => {
    listeners = listeners.filter((l) => l !== listener);
    window.removeEventListener("storage", handleStorage);
  };
}
```

**React context:**

```typescript
interface ThemeContextValue {
  themeId: ThemeId;
  themeDefinition: ThemeDefinition;
  setTheme: (id: ThemeId) => void;
}

const ThemeContext = createContext<ThemeContextValue | null>(null);
```

**ThemeProvider component:**

```typescript
export function ThemeProvider({ children }: { children: ReactNode }) {
  const themeId = useSyncExternalStore(subscribe, getSnapshot);
  const themeDefinition = getTheme(themeId);

  const setTheme = useCallback((id: ThemeId) => {
    localStorage.setItem(STORAGE_KEY, id);
    applyTheme(id, true);
    emitChange();
  }, []);

  return (
    <ThemeContext value={{ themeId, themeDefinition, setTheme }}>
      {children}
    </ThemeContext>
  );
}
```

Note: React 19 supports the shorthand `<Context value={...}>` syntax (no `.Provider`). The codebase already targets React 19 (`"react": "^19.0.0"` in `package.json`).

**useTheme hook:**

```typescript
export function useTheme(): ThemeContextValue {
  const ctx = useContext(ThemeContext);
  if (!ctx) throw new Error("useTheme must be used inside ThemeProvider");
  return ctx;
}
```

Also re-export the types that callers may need:
```typescript
export type { ThemeId, ThemeDefinition } from "@t3tools/shared/theme";
export { THEME_IDS, THEMES, getTheme } from "@t3tools/shared/theme";
```

---

### Step 4: `apps/web/src/hooks/useTheme.ts` (full replacement)

Replace the entire file with a thin re-export barrel. This preserves the import path that `_chat.settings.tsx` and any future callers use:

```typescript
export { useTheme, ThemeProvider } from "../components/ThemeProvider";
export type { ThemeId, ThemeDefinition } from "../components/ThemeProvider";
```

The old API (`theme`, `setTheme`, `resolvedTheme`) is gone. The settings page is updated in Step 8 to use the new API. Because there is only one importer of the old API (`_chat.settings.tsx`), this is a safe swap.

---

### Step 5: `apps/web/src/components/ThemeSelector.tsx` (new file)

A presentational component that renders a radiogroup of swatches.

```typescript
import { useTheme } from "../hooks/useTheme";
import { THEME_IDS, getTheme } from "@t3tools/shared/theme";
import { cn } from "~/lib/utils";

export function ThemeSelector() {
  const { themeId, setTheme } = useTheme();

  return (
    <div className="flex flex-wrap gap-3" role="radiogroup" aria-label="Theme">
      {THEME_IDS.map((id) => {
        const def = getTheme(id);
        const selected = themeId === id;
        return (
          <button
            key={id}
            type="button"
            role="radio"
            aria-checked={selected}
            onClick={() => setTheme(id)}
            className={cn(
              "flex flex-col gap-2 rounded-xl border p-3 text-left transition-shadow focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-ring focus-visible:ring-offset-1 focus-visible:ring-offset-background",
              selected
                ? "border-primary/60 bg-primary/8 ring-1 ring-primary/40"
                : "border-border bg-background hover:bg-accent",
            )}
          >
            {/* Mini color preview grid */}
            <div
              className="h-16 w-32 overflow-hidden rounded-lg"
              style={{ background: def.colors.background }}
              aria-hidden="true"
            >
              {/* Sidebar strip */}
              <div className="flex h-full">
                <div
                  className="w-8 h-full"
                  style={{ background: def.colors.sidebar }}
                />
                <div className="flex flex-1 flex-col">
                  {/* Status bar */}
                  <div
                    className="h-2 w-full"
                    style={{ background: def.colors.statusBar }}
                  />
                  {/* Editor area */}
                  <div
                    className="flex-1"
                    style={{ background: def.colors.editor }}
                  >
                    {/* Accent stripe */}
                    <div
                      className="mt-2 ml-2 h-1 w-8 rounded-full"
                      style={{ background: def.colors.accent }}
                    />
                    <div
                      className="mt-1.5 ml-2 h-1 w-12 rounded-full opacity-40"
                      style={{ background: def.colors.foreground }}
                    />
                  </div>
                  {/* Terminal strip */}
                  <div
                    className="h-5 w-full"
                    style={{ background: def.colors.terminal }}
                  />
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            {/* Label row */}
            <div className="flex items-center justify-between gap-2">
              <span className="text-xs font-medium text-foreground">{def.name}</span>
              {selected && (
                <span className="rounded bg-primary/14 px-1.5 py-0.5 text-[10px] font-medium uppercase tracking-wide text-primary">
                  Active
                </span>
              )}
            </div>
          </button>
        );
      })}
    </div>
  );
}
```

The swatch uses inline `style` for the color values because these are runtime theme colors, not Tailwind utility classes. The layout recreates a mini editor mockup: a sidebar strip on the left, a thin status bar at the top, editor fill in the middle with accent/foreground detail lines, and a terminal strip at the bottom.

